value.value: any structural anomaly of the segmentally patterned skin ridges appearing on the tail of rodents

any anomaly in the reflexive action mediated by cells of the spinal cord, or the involuntary movement reaction caused by the application of a stimulus to an organism; these include signals originating from heat from burning, sharp sensations, and other painful feelings
the extravasation of milky triglyceride-rich chyle into the peritoneal cavity; often a secondary symptom of neoplasms
absence of the primitive epithelial cardiac tube before the division into the chambers of the mature heart
late onset of the induction and/or differentiation of the heart

absence of the anterior portion of the primitive digestive tube of the embryo that lies cephalic to the junction of the yolk stalk, consists of endodermal tissue, and gives rise to the pharynx, lower respiratory system, esophagus, stomach, duodenum proximal to the biliary tract, liver, pancreas, biliary tract, and gall bladder
shortened foregut that terminates abruptly as if having an end or point cut off
underdevelopment of the midfacial region comprising the nasal, maxillary, and zygomatic bones, leading to a concave-looking face
absence of the caudal portion of the primitive digestive tube of the embryo

absence of the brain region derived from the middle of the three cerebral vesicles of the embryo; this region controls sensory and motor functions in the adult, including eye movement and coordination of auditory and visual reflexes
deviation from the average range of midbrain size compared to normal

size reduction or truncation of the brain region derived from the middle of the three cerebral vesicles of the embryo; this region controls sensory and motor functions in the adult, including eye movement and coordination of auditory and visual reflexes

underdevelopment or reduced size, usually due to a reduced number of cells, of the brain region derived from the middle of the three cerebral vesicles of the embryo; this region controls sensory and motor functions in the adult, including eye movement and coordination of auditory and visual reflexes

greater than average size of the brain region derived from the middle of the three cerebral vesicles of the embryo; this region controls sensory and motor functions in the adult, including eye movement and coordination of auditory and visual reflexes
underdevelopment or decreased size, usually due an increased number of cells in the rostral portion of the brain stem

absence of the leftward movement of extra-embryonic fluid at the ventral node; nodal flow is autonomously generated by the rotation of cilia that are tilted toward the posterior on cells of the ventral node and is the central process in symmetry breaking on the left-right axis; when nodal cilia are immotile or absent, nodal flow does not occur
anomaly in the width of the extraembryonic basement membrane that forms on the inner surface of the trophectoderm during placenta morphogenesis and is secreted by the distal parietal endoderm
increased width of the extraembryonic basement membrane that forms on the inner surface of the trophectoderm during placenta morphogenesis and is secreted by the distal parietal endoderm
reduced width of the extraembryonic basement membrane that forms on the inner surface of the trophectoderm during placenta morphogenesis and is secreted by the distal parietal endoderm

anomaly in the size of the middle layer of the placenta between the outermost giant cells and the innermost labyrinth layer; it has a structural role and also produces several layer-specific secreted factors

greater size of the middle layer of the placenta between the outermost giant cells and the innermost labyrinth layer; it has a structural role and also produces several layer-specific secreted factors

reduction of the size of the middle layer of the placenta between the outermost giant cells and the innermost labyrinth layer; it has a structural role and also produces several layer-specific secreted factors
absence of the middle layer of the placenta between the outermost giant cells and the innermost labyrinth layer; it has a structural role and also produces several layer-specific secreted factors
absence of the pupil of the eye

absence of the outermost layer of cells in the blastodermic vesicle, which will develop into the trophoblast layer and then contact the endometrium and take part in establishing the embryo's means of nutrition

any structural anomaly of the flattened, almost circular bilaminar plate of cells formed when the inner cell mass (aka embryoblast) forms two epithelial layers, each of a distinct lineage, separated by an extracellular basement membrane: the external (dorsal) layer is called the epiblast and the internal (ventral) layer is called the hypoblast (aka primitive endoderm); together, they compose the bilaminar embryonic disc
reduced size of the closed space between the embryo and the amnion which contains the amniotic fluid and is formed by the fusion of the parts of the anterior and posterior amniotic folds
late onset of the development and invagination of the embryonic germ layers

definition.value: in the mouse, gastrulation initiates at E6.5, as cells of the primitive ectoderm (epiblast) delaminate at the posterior side of the embryo and ingress through the primitive streak in an epithelial-to-mesenchymal transition

value.value: impaired performance during controlled physical activity
improved performance during controlled physical activity
greater number of the glycogen-accumulating trophoblast cells that arise in the junctional zone of the placenta
reduced number of the glycogen-accumulating trophoblast cells that arise in the junctional zone of the placenta
greater number of the epidermal invaginations from which the hair shaft develops

inability to initiate or maintain the first cell differentiation event in mammalian development, occurring at the late eight-cell stage in the mouse, whereby cells on the outer part of the morula become flattened and bound tightly together with the formation of desmosomes and gap junctions, becoming nearly indistinguishable
increase in the number of trophectoderm cells undergoing programmed cell death
a retrogressive impairment of function or destruction of trophectoderm cells
a congenital anomaly of the eye in which partial or complete corneal opacity is present and resembles the sclera, with no clear boundary between these structures

any anomaly in the radial light dispersion pattern of the iris when a focused light beam is passed through it; particular dispersion pattern anomalies are indicative of abnormalities in iris pigment distribution and for the presence of glaucoma, atrophy and/or infection
anomaly in the expected bronchoconstrictive response to provocation challenge with lipopolysaccharide, bradykinin, histamine or other antigen/allergen or agent, often measured by plethysmography

enhanced or greater than expected bronchoconstrictive response to provocation challenge with lipopolysaccharide, bradykinin, histamine or other antigen/allergen or agent, often measured by plethysmography
reduction in the expected bronchoconstrictive response to provocation challenge with lipopolysaccharide, bradykinin, histamine or other antigen/allergen or agent, often measured by plethysmography
any structural anomaly of the three trophoblast cell layers found in rodent placentas between fetal blood vessels and maternal blood sinuses

definition.value: The human placenta is hemomonochorial, as this membrane consists of a single layer of synctiotrophoblast at term. In mice maternal blood bathes a perforated layer of cytotrophoblast cells that overlay two layers of syncytiotrophoblast, thus the murine placenta is hemotrichorial. Maternal blood has direct access to the murine synctiotrophoblast layer I via fenestrations in the murine cytotrophoblast layer.

value.value: absence of the three trophoblast cell layers found in rodent placentas between fetal blood vessels and maternal blood sinuses
